observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue a directive to the    Municipal Accountant, the General Services Officer and the Municipal Engineer to accomplish within a definite timeline their respective tasks as enumerated in COA Circular No. 2015-008, such as:
the Municipal Engineer to provide the local Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components of road projects;

the Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records     for roads and road components for every road network and disclose       in the Notes to the Financial Statements of the LGU the total road network system; and, 

the GSO maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Department Heads who are designated as Project Coordinators to:
Implement each project funded by the National Government in accordance with the time frame provided in the MOA;
Fast-track the implementation of the delayed/unfinished programs and projects in order to utilize fully the BUB funds and ensure the proper use thereof;
Ensure compliance with the provisions in the MOA and the Work and Financial Plan of the program/project.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant return the unutilized balance from completed projects to the source agencies or to the Bureau of Treasury.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as Chairman of the MDRRM Council, through the MDRRM Officer:
ensure that the PPAs in the MDRRMFIP are specific and aligned with the NDRRM Plan and the corresponding performance indicators are definite, measurable, and time-bounded;
implement the projects identified during the year to achieve the purpose of the fund;
evaluate the unimplemented Programs/Projects/Activities and thresh out the causes of the failure to implement;
revise the Plan, if necessary and see to it that PPAs included in the LDRRMFIP are responsive to the needs of the municipality.
The MDRRM Officer explained that for the project on Desilting of Rivers, a Program of Work was already prepared and the area was already identified for this purpose.  However, this was not identified properly in the MDRRMFIP. The management was amenable to the audit recommendations.

We recommended that the Accountable Officers concerned submit within 30 days from receipt of the AOM, the liquidation reports and its supporting documents, otherwise, restitute/return immediately the amount equivalent to their respective unliquidated cash advances.
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Stop the grant of cash advances to officials and employees with outstanding cash advances;
Issue a directive to the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the salaries of officials and employees who failed to liquidate their cash advances, based on the recommendations of the Municipal Accountant, and;
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Demand from the accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances, the immediate settlement, refund or submission of liquidation reports on the unliquidated cash advances;
Recommend to the Municipal Mayor the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who continue to fail to submit their Liquidation Reports within the period prescribed by regulations;
Recommend to the Municipal Mayor the issuance of demand letters to those accountable officers, who are no longer connected with the LGU, with unliquidated cash advances, and;
Refrain from granting additional cash advance to officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances to avoid accumulation thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 

Compute the monthly depreciation of all Infrastructure Asset, and; 

Record the necessary adjustments on the unrecognized depreciation expenses in order to reflect the correct carrying value of Infrastructure Assets in the books of the LGU.

(39) a. trace back prior years’ transactions with Pag-IBIG Fund to resolve the negative balances of loan amortization payments of the employees to confirm that the amount paid for their loans were not taken from LGU funds;

(40) b. prepare the Disbursement Voucher and its supporting documents for the immediate remittance to Pag-IBIG Fund of prior years’ contributions of the employees; and,

(41) c. reconcile  monthly the SL against the source documents on transactions with Pag-IBIG Fund to avoid accumulation of variances.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 

(48) a. Compute the monthly depreciation of all Infrastructure Asset, and; 

(49) b. Record the necessary adjustments on the unrecognized depreciation expenses in order to reflect the correct carrying value of Infrastructure Assets in the books of the LGU.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
reconstitute a new Inventory Committee to be composed of adequate number of LGU personnel who can be temporarily relieved from their regular duties and responsibilities to devote fully their time on the conduct of physical count of properties until completion following the procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
require the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical    count of all properties of the LGU every year marking each item as government property, prepare and accomplish the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and    Equipment completely as soon as the physical count is concluded and submit it to the Municipal     Accountant and the Audit Team;
require the General Services Officer to perform her duties and responsibilities as the official to be held accountable for all properties of the LGU as embodied in the Local Government Code of 1991 and    to maintain properly the property cards; update the issuance of the PAR and unserviceable properties should be disposed of in    accordance with existing regulations.
Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to regularly    reconcile records pertaining to all properties of the LGU.

